item.title: Boris Johnson Unveils Plan to Ease U.K. Lockdown
item.description: The British prime minister said the U.K. would take some small steps this week in easing the lockdown.

item.title: South Korea's Early Coronavirus Wins Dim After Rash of New Cases
item.description: South Korea, which largely succeeded in quelling the initial spread of the coronavirus, is back on the defensive, with Seoul’s bars and clubs ordered closed, as the country reported its biggest one-day increase in new infections in a month.

item.title: Indian and Chinese Troops in Standoff at Disputed Border
item.description: Indian and Chinese security forces scuffled along the disputed border between the two Asian giants, injuring soldiers on both sides, Indian officials said.

item.title: Venezuela Invasion Was Doomed to Fail
item.description: As details of the botched raid to unseat President Maduro emerge, it has become clear that the plan never came even close to succeeding.

item.title: Older Europeans Reject Calls to Remain in Isolation
item.description: Older generations across Europe are resisting pressure to remain isolated from the rest of society as countries begin to reopen their economies and brace for the possibility of a resurgence in coronavirus infections.

item.title: Should Mild Coronavirus Cases Isolate at Home? Many Asian Countries Say No
item.description: Across swaths of Asia, from China’s coronavirus epicenter of Wuhan to Singapore and South Korea, the well-known strategies of tracing and testing have worked in tandem with a third big logistical task: isolating mild cases outside their homes.
